# React Anti-Pattern Rules (Top 50)

1. Putting server state in Zustand.
2. Fetching data directly in components.
3. Using `useEffect` for primary data fetching instead of query hooks.
4. Missing loading/error/empty UI states.
5. Large god components with mixed concerns.
6. Components exceeding agreed complexity caps.
7. Deep prop drilling across many levels.
8. Unstable list keys (index key on dynamic data).
9. Recreating heavy objects/functions in hot render paths.
10. Overusing context providers that rerender huge trees.
11. Hidden side effects in render functions.
12. Mutating state directly.
13. Ignoring hook dependency rules.
14. Disabling lint rules without design justification.
15. Duplicating API clients across features.
16. Duplicating validation logic by copy-paste.
17. Storing sensitive values in browser storage in plain text.
18. Hardcoding role checks in many components.
19. Missing route guards for privileged screens.
20. Circular imports between features.
21. Using `any` for API/domain types.
22. Skipping runtime validation for external payloads.
23. Not normalizing API error shapes for UI.
24. Triggering broad cache invalidation unnecessarily.
25. Using unstable or ambiguous query keys.
26. No retry/backoff strategy for transient failures.
27. Blocking main thread with heavy sync computations.
28. Rendering huge lists without virtualization.
29. Missing code splitting for heavy pages.
30. Importing server-only libs in client bundle.
31. Side effects at module top-level.
32. Multiple ad-hoc modal and toast systems.
33. CSS and token inconsistency across modules.
34. Excessive wrapper div nesting without semantic value.
35. Missing accessibility labels and keyboard support.
36. Dialogs without focus management.
37. Infinite polling without cancel or visibility handling.
38. Optimistic updates without rollback behavior.
39. Complex forms built only with ad-hoc `useState`.
40. Unclear separation between UI state and domain state.
41. Snapshot-only tests without behavior assertions.
42. E2E-only confidence without unit/component tests.
43. No regression tests for fixed frontend bugs.
44. Unbounded page-level data loading.
45. Hydration mismatch due to client-only assumptions.
46. Layout shift from missing skeleton/placeholder sizing.
47. Mixing transport DTO and UI view model without mapping.
48. No route-level error boundaries.
49. Silent promise failures in event handlers.
50. Shipping without performance regression checks.
